<BlogPost
	title="The March Consistency Check - ClimbHQ"
	heroTitle="The March Consistency Check"
	category="Strategy"
	date="March 2026"
	readTime="6 min read"
	description="As Q1 ends, three questions every climbing centre owner should ask to identify what's working, where people linger, and what quietly faded after January."
>
	<div class="blog-lead">
		<p>As Q1 comes to an end, March is a good moment to pause and ask three simple questions.</p>
	</div>

	<section>
		<h2>What is now predictable in your centre?</h2>
		<p>Look back over the last four weeks.</p>
		<p>Which sessions are consistently busy? Which evenings have developed a strong community feel? Which events bring people back week after week?</p>
		<p>If something has happened three or four weeks in a row, it probably isn't luck.</p>

		<blockquote class="blog-pullquote">
			It's a pattern. And patterns are worth protecting.
		</blockquote>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>Where do people linger?</h2>
		<p>Belonging often appears in the moments between the climbs.</p>
		<p>Notice where climbers stop to talk. Which sessions run slightly over time. Where people sit after they've finished climbing.</p>

		<div class="blog-insight">
			<p class="blog-insight-label">Key insight</p>
			<p>These small moments often tell you more than attendance numbers.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>What quietly faded after January?</h2>
		<p>January is full of ideas and experiments.</p>
		<p>Some stick. Some don't.</p>
		<p>March is a useful time to notice which initiatives kept going and which ones lost momentum.</p>
		<p>This isn't failure. It's information.</p>

		<blockquote class="blog-pullquote">
			It tells you where your real community energy sits.
		</blockquote>
	</section>

	<figure class="blog-image">
		<img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="800" height="450" src="/images/stock/climbing-in-gym.jpg" alt="Climbers in a gym community session" />
